<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1896-01-22T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1896-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="342" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d342">
                            <head><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Olney</persName> to
                                    Mr. <persName type="to">Eustis</persName></hi>.</head>
                            <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg></opener>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1896-01-22"><hi rend="italic">January 22,
                                        1896</hi></date>.</dateline></opener>
                            <p>Would not French citizen maltreated on voyage, as Waller alleges
                                himself to have been, have right to sue French Government for
                                damages as well as private individuals? If there is doubt on the
                                point take Clunet’s opinion. In this connection, was or was not
                                Waller during voyage in custody of ship or of French military
                                authorities? Cable answer.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Olney</hi></signed>.</closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>